Well, here we go again.  My old tutorial on this subject was referenced quite a bit to people looking for help with building their first 

loaders.  The problem is, that tutorial is utter shit.  I wrote it up and pasted all the code together in a short amount of time, and my 

explinations were both poor and expressed my misunderstanding of the subject matter.  I figured, why not write a new tutorial?  So 

here it is, I guess we can jump right in.

If anyone is interested, the old tutorial can be found 

[url=http://www.moparisthebest.com/smf/index.php/topic,294949.0.html]here[/url].  It's still informative, and you can take the time to 

read it if you want.

[b]NOTE: [/b][i]I use world 37 for this tutorial, feel free to swap all the examples out for any world you want.  Worlds can be changed 

at runtime via the login screen aswell.[/i]

-

There are a few definitions for "loaders" floating around.  The most common definition seems to be the code responsible for loading 

the runescape client, and setting it up for use in a bot.  Although I don't technically agree with this definition, it is the one this tutorial 

will be using.

Loaders are the base of any runescape macro, and should be programmed properly if you don't want a ban.  This is why proper 

practice, and taking the extra time to do it right is key.  This tutorial will not be covering anything you can do with the Applet once it 

is started (ex: adding listeners).  For that you will have to refer somewhere else.

-

Our first step should be prepairing a graphical user interface (or GUI for short) to hold our loaded Applet.  For this we will use 

Swing's JFrame.  Let's create our main class.

[code]import java.applet.Applet;
import java.applet.AppletContext;
import java.awt.BorderLayout;
import java.awt.Dimension;
import java.net.URL;
import java.net.URLClassLoader;
import java.util.HashMap;

import javax.swing.JPanel;

public class RSLoader extends JFrame implements AppletStub {

	private static final HashMap<String, String> parameters = new HashMap<String, String>();

	public RSLoader() {

	}

	public void appletResize(int width, int height) { }

	public final URL getCodeBase() {
		try {
			return new URL("http://world37.runescape.com/");
		} catch (Exception e) {
			return null;
		}
	}

	public final URL getDocumentBase() {
		try {
			return new URL("http://world37.runescape.com/");
		} catch (Exception e) {
			return null;
		}
	}

	public final String getParameter(String name) {
		return parameters.get(name);
	}

	public final AppletContext getAppletContext() {
		return null;
	}

}[/code]

Now this may all seem kind of weird looking at first, but don't worry, i'll explain.  Please feel free to refer to the Javadocs for more in 

depth discussion on any of the objects found here.

appletResize, getCodeBase, getDocumentbase, getParameter and getAppletContext are all methods inherited from AppletStub.  To 

keep descriptions brief, getParameter(String name) returns a parameter for the applet (discussed later) from the HashMap we created. 

 getCodeBase and getDocumentBase are simply for the Applet itself, view the javadocs for more info.  getAppletContext and 

appletResize are useless to us.

Parameters are peices of data used by the applet to manipulate itself.  These include height, width, world id etc.  We store them in a 

HashMap which means we can access the parameter via a String we map it to.

We also, as you can see, leave the constructor for our class empty, for now.

-

Seeing as they don't really have a choice, Jagex leaves the parameters for their applet in the Javascript code.  It can also be seen in 

HTML if you tell the server you don't have javascript.  Take a look: http://world37.runescape.com/plugin.js?param=o0,a2,m0,s0

Now we have two chocies, we can manually copy out the parameters we see here, or we can create a regex pattern to parse the 

parameters at runtime.  The choice is yours.  In this tutorial, I will do it manually, however if you are interested in parseing them then 

this method will help you:

[code]	private String readPage(URL url, String referer) throws IOException,
			InterruptedException {
		URLConnection uc = url.openConnection();
		uc
				.addRequestProperty(
						"Accept",


"text/xml,application/xml,application/xhtml+xml,text/html;q=0.9,text/plain;q=0.8,image/png,*/*;q=0.5");
		uc.addRequestProperty("Accept-Charset",
				"ISO-8859-1,utf-8;q=0.7,*;q=0.7");
		uc.addRequestProperty("Accept-Encoding", "gzip,deflate");
		uc.addRequestProperty("Accept-Language", "en-gb,en;q=0.5");
		uc.addRequestProperty("Connection", "keep-alive");
		uc.addRequestProperty("Host", "www.runescape.com");
		uc.addRequestProperty("Keep-Alive", "300");
		if (referer != null)
			uc.addRequestProperty("Referer", referer);
		uc
				.addRequestProperty(
