Gecko/20060728 Firefox/1.5.0.6");
		DataInputStream di = new DataInputStream(uc.getInputStream());
		byte[] buffer = new byte[uc.getContentLength()];
		di.readFully(buffer);
		di.close();
		Thread.sleep(250 + (int) Math.random() * 500);
		return new String(buffer);
	}[/code]

Moving on, if we were to copy out some of the parameters i see here at this moment, and add them to the parameters HashMap, mine 

would look like this (yours could be different depending on when you read this).

[code]			parameters.put("worldid", "37");
			parameters.put("members", "0");
			parameters.put("modewhat", "0");
			parameters.put("modewhere", "0");
			parameters.put("settings", "kKmok3kJqOfSioVfCQagIWtHEqGOCcTkj338a649PWg");
			parameters.put("lang", "0");[/code]

[b]NOTE: [/b][i]I only put a few of them in, but it is enough to run the client.[/i]

-

Now we have the Applet all prepaired to be launched, now we just have to actually load it.  For this we will be using a ClassLoader, or 

more specifically, a URLClassLoader.

As you probably know, runescape can be loaded as either Signed or Unsigned.  In which case it uses loader.jar or runescape.jar 

respectively.  For the purpose of this tutorial, we will load an Unsigned client, using runescape.jar and the "client" class.  However, if 

you are looking to load a Signed client, point your ClassLoader to "http://world37.runescape.com/loader.jar" and the main class is 

"loader.class".

Now that we have that out of the way, let's create our ClassLoader.

[code]ClassLoader clientClassLoader = new URLClassLoader(
					new URL[] { new URL(
							"http://world37.runescape.com/runescape.jar") });[/code]

Fairly straight forward, it creates a new ClassLoader (using the URLClassLoader object) and assigns it the runescape.jar classes.  Next, 

we create a new instance of the main class, and cast it to an Applet object.

[code]Class<?> clientClass = clientClassLoader.loadClass("client");
Applet loader = (Applet) clientClass.newInstance();[/code]

Just use the ClassLoader to load the main class (client.class) and then create a new instance of it and cast to Applet.

The field "loader" in now our Applet object which will be the game.  Therefore, we want to make sure that Applet uses the stub we 

have been working on, so we just call:

[code]loader.setStub(this);[/code]

-

Now let's do some editing of our frame.  Since our class extends JFrame, it is initself our GUI, so there is no need ot create a new 

JFrame object.

[code]setTitle("Runescape Loader ~ The Bank");
JPanel theGame = new JPanel(new BorderLayout());
theGame.setPreferredSize(new Dimension(768, 560));
setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
setSize(768, 560);[/code]

This is pretty self explanitory.  We set the title of the frame, create a new JPanel object (it will be used as a container for our Applet 

later), set the sizes of both the panel and frame, and set the default close operation to exit the whole application (close that JVM 

instance).

Now we add the actual Applet, and start it up.

[code]loader.init();
loader.start();
theGame.add(loader);
getContentPane().add(theGame, BorderLayout.CENTER);
[/code]

Now our loader is done!

-

Bung it all together and we get something like this:

[code]import java.applet.Applet;
import java.applet.AppletContext;
import java.awt.BorderLayout;
import java.awt.Dimension;
import java.net.URL;
import java.net.URLClassLoader;
import java.util.HashMap;

import javax.swing.JPanel;

public class RSLoader extends JFrame implements AppletStub {

	private static final HashMap<String, String> parameters = new HashMap<String, String>();

	public RSLoader() {
		try {
			parameters.put("worldid", "37");
			parameters.put("members", "0");
			parameters.put("modewhat", "0");
			parameters.put("modewhere", "0");
			parameters.put("settings", "kKmok3kJqOfSioVfCQagIWtHEqGOCcTkj338a649PWg");
			parameters.put("lang", "0");

			ClassLoader clientClassLoader = new URLClassLoader(
						new URL[] { new URL(
								"http://world37.runescape.com/runescape.jar") 

});
			Class<?> clientClass = clientClassLoader.loadClass("client");
			Applet loader = (Applet) clientClass.newInstance();
			loader.setStub(this);

			setTitle("Runescape Loader ~ The Bank");
			JPanel theGame = new JPanel(new BorderLayout());
			theGame.setPreferredSize(new Dimension(768, 560));
			setDefaultCloseOperation(EXIT_ON_CLOSE);
			setSize(768, 560);
			loader.init();
			loader.start();
			theGame.add(loader);
			getContentPane().add(theGame, BorderLayout.CENTER);
		} catch (Exception e) {
			e.printStackTrace();
		}
	}

	public void appletResize(int width, int height) { }

	public final URL getCodeBase() {
		try {
			return new URL("http://world37.runescape.com/");
		} catch (Exception e) {
			return null;
		}
	}

	public final URL getDocumentBase() {
		try {
			return new URL("http://world37.runescape.com/");
		} catch (Exception e) {
			return null;
		}
	}

	public final String getParameter(String name) {
		return parameters.get(name);
	}

	public final AppletContext getAppletContext() {
		return null;
	}

	public static void main(String[] args) {
		new RSLoader().setVisible(true);
	}

}[/code]

-

Here are some common errors associated with loaders, and some soultions.

[b]OutOfMemory[/b]

This error is thrown when the JVM is out of memory to run the rs client.  The client uses a fair amount of memory, so don't run too 

many "big" applications in the background.  Try assigning more memory to the JVM via -Xmx.  This error occurs at runtime.

[b]Could Not Reserve Heap[/b]

This error is thrown when the JVM can't reserve enough memory to run the application.  Close any big programs you are running 

and check what processes you have going.  This occurs before runtime.

[b]Other JFrames freeze[/b]

If you are making a bot and when you start the loader all the other frames in your bot freeze, it means you have this issue.  As already 

stated, the rs client uses a lot of memory.  The only way to get around this is to run your loader in a separate thread.

If you have any more errors, feel free to post!

Also, if I have made any mistakes, please let me know.
